Euphorbia heterophylla is a species of flowering plant in the spurge family.
It is also commonly referred to as wild poinsettia or fire-on-the-mountain.
It typically grows up to three feet tall and has a bushy appearance with dense foliage.
The leaves of Euphorbia heterophylla are highly variable, ranging from green to red and purple in color.
The plant produces small, greenish-yellow flowers that are clustered in bracts at the end of the stems.
Euphorbia heterophylla is native to tropical and subtropical regions and is often found in fields, waste areas, and along roadsides.
The plant is considered a weed in some areas due to its tendency to grow rapidly and compete with cultivated crops.
